@node bricks
@{b}
Bricks 
@{ub}
It all started one morning when a group of builders returned to their
construction site to find that their unfinished building had been ravaged
by what looked like small explosions. The partly destroyed buildings were
covered in splatters of blood, and further trails led off into the grass.

The builders could find no trace of who or what had done this damage, and
they spent the rest of the day rebuilding the damaged brickwork.

The next morning the builders found their work ruined again. In an effort to
protect their handiwork they put up an electric fence and bought in guard 
dogs, but neither of these measures prevented the bricks being damaged.

In a final act of desperation, one of the builders set up his video camera
to monitor the site overnight. The next morning the site was once again a 
wreck. The builders played back the video tape, and this is what they saw...

(See also @{"Wood" link wood} and @{"Construct" link construct})
@endnode
@node pencils
@{b}
Pencils
@{ub}
The Worms tribes had almost run out of pencils, and so a great meeting was
called.

The tribes met in the centre of Wormville around their one remaining pencil,
and they talked, they argued, they discussed, and, in the end, they came to
the same conclusion that people through the ages had come to.
@{i}
Somebody steals all the pencils.
@{ui}
The worms, being the violent, bloodthirsty lot that they were, decided to do
something about it. They set a trap using their last pencil, which was
placed in a cage withthe door open, and then they waited.

Sure enough, just after midnight, a tiny gnome crept into the Wormville,
spotted the pencil, and went to get it. The worms slammed the cage door
after him and locked it.

At first the gnome was reluctant to discuss where he'd taken all the 
pencils. However, the Worms presented a convincing argument, pointing out
the injustice of stealing, their basic right to own pencils, and the fact
that they had more weaponry than the entire cast of Starship Troopers in
the next room, coupled with the fact that there were plenty of gnomes about,
and the world wasn't going to miss one.

Dazzled by the blinding logic of the Worms arguments, the gnome reluctantly
agreed to take the Worms to the place he kept the world's stolen pencils.
Without a word of warning, he whipped out his huge wand and waved it around.
The Worms were magically transported to a special place down the back of
the Sofa of the Universe, where there were more than enough pencils to go
around.

 But the Worms didn't want to share. There was only one sensible solution.
But the Worms decided to have a big fight instead!
@endnode
@node rome
@{b}
Rome
@{ub}
The real reason for the fall of the Roman Empire. Nuff said!
@endnode
@node Toyland
@{b}
Toyland
@{ub}
Toyland was created by Worm elders as a place for young Worms to train. The
bright, colourful design was considered for young Worms. If any actually
survived their training was considered complete...

(See also @{"Metal" link metal} and @{"Flat" link flat})
@endnode
@node custard
@{b}
Custard
@{ub}
When the great Worm inventor, Thaddeus P. Worm, announced he'd discovered
an ancient recipe or making napalm out of eggs, milk and sugar, the Worms
were delighted and instructed him to start production immediately.

Unfortunately Thaddeus, being a little short sighted, had confused the word
Napalm with the word Custard. That didn't stop him producing fifteen tonnes 
of the stuff and flooding Wormville. He even produced a huge cherry from
somewhere.

The other Worms couldn't decide whose fault it had been, and decided to
settle things in the only way they knew - bloody combat!
@endnode
